questionTemplates.text:
W: Hey, Tim. My uncle died last weekend. His funeral is on Thursday, so I can't work. Can you work for me tomorrow?
M: Sorry, Jenny, but I have a soccer game on Thursday. You should ask Melinda to take your shift. I think she got back from vacation yesterday.
{a}

M: Good morning. I'd like to speak to Mr. Adams, please. This is Edward Miller at Sun Valley Health center.
M: Mr. Miller, my husband isn't at home. I can give you his business number, if you'd like to call him at work.
{a}

W: What do you think of the apple pie? I made it myself.
M: Very delicious indeed. Even my mother's cannot match this.
{a}

M: Have you heard of Professor Smith? I'm thinking of taking an advanced engineering course with him. What do you think?
W: Yeah! You really should. He's published dozens of books so far, once been recommended as a textbook for postgraduates.
{a}

F: Where is Jim?
M: He has gone to England with his family. He won't be back until September.
{a}

M: Why did Mary give Jim flowers?
W: I think yesterday was Jim's birthday.
{a}

W: Excuse me, sir. How can I get to this hotel? I can't find it.
M: It's easy. Just go along this street to 26th Avenue. And then you'll find it next to the hank.
{a}

F: What time is it now?
M: A quarter to eleven.
{a}

W: What is that noise?
M: That is Robert sawing the broken tree in his back yard.
{a}

M: What does your husband do?
F: He teaches Spanish.
{a}

M: Have you heard about Tim? He had to be rushed to the emergency room.
W: Really? I hope it's not too serious.
{a}

M: My dinner tastes kind of funny.
W: Then why don't you have the waiter bring you something else?
{a}

M: I'm not feeling so well.
W: Get some rest and take these three times a day and you should feel better. If you don't, come back and see me.
{a}

F: Can you help my son Peter with his English, Mr. Black?
M: OK, Mrs. Green.
{a}

M: Do you want to see if I can get tickets to the football game next week?
W: I don't think we can have a chance, but you can try anyway.
{a}

M: I wonder if Sue will be here by 5 o'clock.
W: Her husband said she left home at 4:30. She should be here at 5:10, or 5:15 at the latest.
{a}

F: Excuse me, can you tell me the way to the cinema?
M: Yes. Go along this road and turn right at the second crossing.
{a}

M: Forgive the mess in here, we had a party last night. There were a lot of people and they all brought food.
W: Yeah, I can tell. Well, I guess it's pretty obvious what you'll be doing most of today.
{a}

M: I can't find my pen. I need to write a letter.
W: I'll look for it later. Right now I need you to help fix the shelf before paint it.
{a}

W: Could you please give me a lift to the airport this aftemoon? I need to catch a flight.
M: I'd like to, but there is something wrong with my car. Why not ask Jim for help? He has had his car fixed and he's free today.
{a}

W: Wow, your new house is so beautiful.
M: Thank you. But I think it still needs some more decoration.
{a}

M: Would you pass me the Sports Section please?
W: Sure, if you give me the classified Ads and Local-News Section.
{a}

M: I am looking for someone who has taken care of elderly people before. Do you have any experience?
W: I'm sorry. My experience is with small children. I'm afraid I will not be suitable for the job.
{a}

W: I'd like to have my car serviced, the engine and wheels checked. How long will that take?
M: Oh, well, it's rather late. I'm afraid it'll take hours. You have to have it done in the morning, but we can lend you a car like yours free of charge. You can take it now.
{a}

M: I'm getting absolutely nowhere with Physics problems.
W: How about my going through them with you?
{a}
